{{short description|Japanese deity}} {{refimprove|date=November 2020}}
'''Wakumusubi''' (和久産巣日神) is a [[kami]] of agriculture. In many versions, he was born from the urine of [[Izanami]] when she died.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Wakumusubi • A History of Japan - 日本歴史|url=https://historyofjapan.co.uk/wiki/wakumusubi/|access-date=2020-11-13|website=A History of Japan - 日本歴史|language=en-GB}}</ref> Another version of the Nihon Shoki states he was a child of [[Kagu-tsuchi|Kagutsuchi]] and [[Haniyasu-hiko and Haniyasu-hime|Haniyasu-hime]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Encyclopedia of Shinto詳細|url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9734|archive-url=|access-date=2021-09-28|website=國學院大學デジタルミュージアム|language=ja}}</ref>
He is enshrined at [[Iwama Dōjō#Aiki Jinja|Aiki Jinja]].<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Cali|first1=Joseph|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J1gEEAAAQBAJ&dq=Wakumusubi&pg=PA173|title=Shinto Shrines: A Guide to the Sacred Sites of Japan's Ancient Religion|last2=Dougill|first2=John|date=2012-11-30|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=978-0-8248-3775-4|pages=173|language=en}}</ref>
{{Infobox deity | type = Shinto | name = Wakumusubi | god_of = Agriculture | siblings = [[Mizuhanome]] | children = [[Toyouke-Ōmikami|Toyouke]] | parents = [[Izanami]] }}He is the brother of [[Mizuhanome]]. He is also the father of [[Toyouke-Ōmikami]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Encyclopedia of Shinto - Home : Kami in Classic Texts : Toyoukehime|url=http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=158|access-date=2020-11-14|website=eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp}}</ref>
== Faith == * {{ill|Atago Shrine (Kyoto)|ja|愛宕神社}}（Kyoto City）、 * {{ill|Takekoma Inari Shrine|ja|竹駒神社|Takekoma Inari Shrine=Takekoma Inari Shrine|lt=Takekoma Shrine}}（Miyagi Prefecture）、 * {{ill|Asaka Kokuzō Shrine|ja|安積国造神社}}（Fukushima Prefecture）、 * {{ill|Makata Shrine|ja|麻賀多神社}}（Chiba Prefecture）
== See also ==
